\begin_layout Paragraph*
Keep Gem Mine at level 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned above you need Gem Mine level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

1 early.
 As early as you can.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gems are important, but there is a gotcha that catches many players.
 Often new players assume that the higher the level of the mine, the better.
 It is, but not early in the game.
 Upgrading Gem Mine before level 70 (even to level 2) is considered a mistake,
 and truly slows you down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each level of Gem Mine slightly improves the stats of the gems you receive,
 but there is a trade off.
 With each next level the price of gems increases (they cost more gold,
 wood and stone), and so does the time required to mine them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, with Gem Mine level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

1 a single gem costs 150 gold, 2 wood and 1 stone, and takes 42 minutes
 to find a gem (with Laborers' Quarters level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

6, also called just Lab).
 In comparision, with Gem Mine level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

6 gems cost 900 gold, 400 wood and 133 stone, and take 5 hours and 36 minutes
 to harvest (with same level of Lab).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you can see the time needed to find a gem inflates a lot with each next
 level, which means you get less gems.
 Unfortunately you can't use all gems, as only some gems are suitable for
 your character.
 That means you could have waited for hours for a single gem only to find
 it is for the wrong class (yep, the RNG god often gives you gems for other
 classes, or luck gems, which are considered useless).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What's worse, the gold price also inflates a lot, and before level 50 you
 will find it hard to collect enough even for the gems that cost only 150
 gold.
 Early in the game you level up quickly and need that gold for so many other
 things (guild skills, stats, starting raids, buying epics).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And on top of all that, the more time needed to mine a gem, the more expensive
 it is to skip waiting with mushrooms.
 This is the very reason why fast-leveling try-hard players keep Gem Mine
 at level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

1 until their character reaches 215-225 level.
 To level up quickly they need to change gems very often, and having the
 mine at level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

1 means that skipping a single gem costs only a few mushrooms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Don't upgrade Smithy beyond level 9
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At server start, don't rush to build the Smithy yet.
 Do that only when you can't win enough attacks anymore (usually around
 the time you have Fortress 10-11 ready).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Level
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

9 of Smithy allows you to upgrade your soldiers to level 70, and at that
 level training one soldier costs 346 wood and 112 stone.
 At the beginning of a new server level 70 is more than adequate to defeat
 just enough opponents, and the cost of the soldiers is low enough to allow
 you to attack opponents that give no resources, just to force a change
 of the opponent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You might even manage to do just fine without ever building Smithy.
 Possible if you manage to find active players to exchange fortress counter-atta
cks with, as long as those players have no defences (no one should, right?).
\end_layout

